<biogHist>
<abstract>Hope Cottage opened in 1887. It was a lying-in Home for single mothers giving birth to their first babies. Many of the mothers may have have been only 14 years old. The Home closed in the early twentieth century.</abstract>
<p>Grace Soltau, the first president of the Woman's Christian Temperance Union, established Hope Cottage. In 1892, she handed it over to Maud Montgomery, the Anglican Bishop of Tasmania's wife and the founder of the Anglican run Home of Mercy. A committee in Launceston was supposed to manage Hope Cottage but there was little interest in it and responsibility largely fell to the Rector of St John's and his wife. Hope Cottage eventually amalgamated with the Home of Mercy.</p>
<p>According to Geoffrey Stephens, the historian of Clarendon Children's Home which developed out of the Home of Mercy, many of the mothers at Hope Cottage were 14 years old.</p>
